<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Species delineation can be problematic in the presence of morphological ambiguities due to phenotypic plasticity and convergence (e.g., cryptic species), especially in mollusks (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10682-009-9350-0" author="Zieritz, A" journalOrPublisher="Evolutionary Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="923 - 938" refId="B29" refString="Zieritz, A, Hoffman, JI, Amos, W, Aldridge, DC, 2010. Phenotypic plasticity and genetic isolation-by-distance in the freshwater mussel Unio pictorum (Mollusca: Unionoida). Evolutionary Ecology 24 (4): 923 - 938, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10682-009-9350-0" title="Phenotypic plasticity and genetic isolation-by-distance in the freshwater mussel Unio pictorum (Mollusca: Unionoida)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10682-009-9350-0" volume="24" year="2010">Zieritz et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/ece3.649" author="Inoue, K" journalOrPublisher="Ecology and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="2670 - 2683" refId="B13" refString="Inoue, K, Hayes, DM, Harris, JL, Christian, AD, 2013. Phylogenetic and morphometric analyses reveal ecophenotypic plasticity in freshwater mussels Obovaria jacksoniana and Villosa arkansasensis (B ivalvia: Unionidae). Ecology and Evolution 3 (8): 2670 - 2683, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/ece3.649" title="Phylogenetic and morphometric analyses reveal ecophenotypic plasticity in freshwater mussels Obovaria jacksoniana and Villosa arkansasensis (B ivalvia: Unionidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/ece3.649" volume="3" year="2013">Inoue et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The use of molecular genetics can aid species delineation in the case of phenotypic plasticity and/or convergence (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/biolinnean/bly046" author="Pieri, AM" journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="261 - 277" refId="B22" refString="Pieri, AM, Inoue, K, Johnson, NA, Smith, CH, Harris, JL, Robertson, C, Randklev, CR, 2018. Molecular and morphometric analyses reveal cryptic diversity within freshwater mussels (Bivalvia: Unionidae) of the western Gulf coastal drainages of the USA. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 124 (2): 261 - 277, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/biolinnean/bly046" title="Molecular and morphometric analyses reveal cryptic diversity within freshwater mussels (Bivalvia: Unionidae) of the western Gulf coastal drainages of the USA." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/biolinnean/bly046" volume="124" year="2018">Pieri et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0200956" author="Wu, RW" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Biology and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" refId="B28" refString="Wu, RW, Liu, YT, Wang, S, Liu, XJ, Zanatta, DT, Roe, KJ, Song, XL, An, CT, Wu, XP, 2018. Testing the utility of DNA barcodes and a preliminary phylogenetic framework for Chinese freshwater mussels (Bivalvia: Unionidae) from the middle and lower Yangtze River. PLoS ONE 13: e0200956. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0200956" title="Testing the utility of DNA barcodes and a preliminary phylogenetic framework for Chinese freshwater mussels (Bivalvia: Unionidae) from the middle and lower Yangtze River. PLoS ONE 13: e 0200956." url="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0200956" year="2018">Wu et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wu &amp; Wu" authorityYear="2021" class="Bivalvia" family="Unionidae" genus="Inversidens" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Inversidens rentianensis" order="Unionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="rentianensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Inversidens rentianensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. can be distinguished from congeneric species based on diagnostic characteristics of the shell. In this study, we also analyzed the interspecific divergence between 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kobelt" baseAuthorityYear="1879" class="Bivalvia" family="Unionidae" genus="Inversidens" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Inversidens brandtii" order="Unionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brandtii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Inversidens brandtii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wu &amp; Wu" authorityYear="2021" class="Bivalvia" family="Unionidae" genus="Inversidens" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Inversidens rentianensis" order="Unionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="rentianensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Inversidens rentianensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. based on the COI barcode. The results showed that the average interspecific divergence between the two species was 10.1%, which was much higher than intraspecific divergences. Genetic analysis conducted in this study supports 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. rentianensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="rentianensis">
